{"title_page": "Patrick Willis", "text_new": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{For|the judge|Patrick Willis (judge)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Patrick Willis\n|image=Patrick Willis in 2012.jpg\n|image_size=180\n|alt=\n|caption=Willis with the San Francisco 49ers in 2012\n|number=52\n|position=[[Linebacker#Middle linebacker|Middle linebacker]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1985|1|25|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Bruceton, Tennessee]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=1\n|weight_lbs=240\n|high_school=[[Hollow Rock-Bruceton Central High School|Bruceton (TN) Central]]\n|college=[[Ole Miss Rebels football|Mississippi]]\n|draftyear=2007\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=11\n|pastteams=\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n|highlights=\n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2008 Pro Bowl|2007]]\u2013[[2014 Pro Bowl|2013]])\n* 5\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2007 All-Pro Team|2007]], [[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]]\u2013[[2013 All-Pro Team|2012]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2008 All-Pro Team|2008]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2007|2007]])\n* [[Butkus Award|Butkus Award (pro)]] (2009)\n* [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]] (2007)\n* [[ Big Dick Award|Big Dick Award (college)]] (2006)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2005 College Football All-America Team|2005]], [[2006 College Football All-America Team|2006]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2005 All-SEC football team|2005]], [[2006 All-SEC football team|2006]])\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n|statvalue1=950\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack]]s\n|statvalue2=20.5\n|statlabel3=[[Interception]]s\n|statvalue3=8\n|statlabel4=Forced [[fumble]]s\n|statvalue4=16\n|statlabel5=[[Touchdown]]s\n|statvalue5=2\n|nflnew=patrickwillis/2495781\n|CollegeHOF=2444\n}}\n\n'''Patrick L. Willis''' (born January 25, 1985) is a former [[American football]] [[linebacker]] who played his entire eight-year career with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He was drafted by the 49ers in the first round of the [[2007 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Ole Miss Rebels football|University of Mississippi]] and received consensus [[All-American]] honors.\n\nDuring Willis's senior season at Ole Miss, he received the [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] and the [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] as the nation's top linebacker. A year later as a member of the 49ers, Willis led the NFL in tackles, earned first-team [[All-Pro]] and [[Pro Bowl]] honors while being named the 2007 [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year|AP NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]].  Willis made the Pro Bowl in his first seven seasons in the NFL, and earned All-Pro honors in his first six years. He won the college Butkus Award in 2006 while at [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] and in 2009, he won the professional Butkus Award while with the 49ers.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Bruceton, Tennessee]], Willis grew up in abject poverty and had to take care of his younger siblings. By the age of 10, he worked full-time in cotton fields.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/07/patrick-willis_n_5405702.html |title=A Troubled Childhood Shaped Patrick Willis Into A Forgiving Adult And An NFL Powerhouse |last=Schultz |first=Jordan |date=July 7, 2014 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=July 17, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> At age 17, he left his home, a [[double-wide]] in a [[trailer park]] just outside Bruceton, with his brothers, Orey and Detris, and sister, Ernicka, when his alcoholic father turned increasingly violent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/49ers/2012/09/19/patrick-willis-in-powerful-commercial|title=49ers Web Blog: Patrick Willis in powerful commercial/ | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> The siblings moved in with Willis's high school basketball coach.\n\nWillis attended [[Hollow Rock-Bruceton Central High School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrbk12.org/Docs/alumni/2000s/2003/patrick_willis/2003_patrick_willis.htm |title=Patrick Willis |publisher=Hrbk12.org |accessdate=October 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726155354/http://www.hrbk12.org/Docs/alumni/2000s/2003/patrick_willis/2003_patrick_willis.htm |archive-date=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> where he was a two-time All-State selection, Regional Most Valuable Player, and West Tennessee Player of the Year. He earned four letters in football and basketball, and three in baseball. He was also the first person in Tennessee state history to be nominated for both the Mr. Football Award for a Lineman (as a linebacker) and the Mr. Football Award for a Back (as a tailback) in the same season.\n\nRegarded as a three-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Willis was listed as the No. 60 linebacker prospect in the class of 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-183 |title=Inside linebackers 2003 |work=Rivals.com |date=February 5, 2010 }}</ref> He chose Ole Miss over Memphis.\n\n{{college athlete recruit start|40=yes|year=2003}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit      = Patrick Willis\n| position     = [[Linebacker|LB]]\n| hometown     = Bruceton, Tennessee\n| highschool   = Central HS\n| feet         = 6\n| inches       = 2\n| weight       =217\n| 40           = 4.6\n| commitdate   = July 8, 2003\n| scout stars  = 2\n| rivals stars = 3\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               = yes\n| year             = 2003\n| rivals ref title = 2003 Mississippi Football Commitment List\n| scout ref title  = 2003 Ole Miss College Football Team Recruiting Prospects\n| rivals school    = olemiss\n| scout s          = 177\n| scout overall    = 32 (college recruiting)\n| rivals overall   = 60 (LB); 38 (college recruiting)\n| accessdate       = August 17, 2013\n| rivals archiveurl=\n| scout archiveurl =\n| espn archiveurl  =\n}}\n\n==College career==\n{{Cquote|Patrick leads by example. He is not a big talker. He just gets in there and does his job every day and makes everybody around him better.|15px|15px|former Mississippi coach [[Ed Orgeron]].<ref name=\"ColstonUSAToday\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Colston |author2= |title=Hardship toughened Willis for NFL's rigors |work=[[USA Today]] |page= |date=March 17, 2007 |accessdate= |quote= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/draft/2007-03-14-patrick-willis_N.htm }}</ref>}}\n\nWillis attended the [[University of Mississippi]] (\"Ole Miss\"), and played for the [[Ole Miss Rebels football]] team from 2003 to 2006.  As a freshman at Ole Miss, Willis played in all 13 games and made 20 stops. He received the Scholar-Athlete Award from the Ole Miss chapter of the [[National Football Foundation]] and [[College Football Hall of Fame]].\n\nAs a sophomore in 2004, he appeared in 10 of 11 games and earned honorable mention All-[[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) honors from the Associated Press. He recorded 70 tackles (54 solo), and led the team with 11.0 tackles for a loss and five sacks.\n\nIn Willis's 2005 junior campaign, he led the SEC in total tackles at 12.80 per game, which placed him sixth nationally. He finished season with 128 total tackles, 9.5 tackles for loss, three sacks, an interception, two forced fumbles and a fumble recovery. Willis was named SEC Defensive Player of the Year by CollegeFootballNews.com and [[Scout.com]]. He was also named as a first-team All-American by College Football News and the All-American Football Foundation. Willis earned first-team All-SEC honors from the Associated Press, SEC Coaches, CollegeFootballNews.com and Rivals.com.<ref name=\"First_Team\">{{cite web|author1= |url=https://olemisssports.com/news/2006/2/27/Patrick_Willis_Named_First_Team_All_America_By_All_American_Football_Foundation.aspx |title=Patrick Willis Named First Team All-America By All-American Football Foundation |website=Ole Miss Football |date=27 February 2006 |accessdate=October 31, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring Willis's last collegiate year in 2006, he led the SEC in tackles once again with 11.4 per game and collected 137 tackles, 11.5 TFLs, seven passes deflected, three sacks, two forced fumbles and one fumble recovery. He was awarded SEC Defensive Player of the Year, first-team All-SEC, and consensus first-team [[2006 College Football All-America Team|All-American]]. He was the winner of the [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] and the prestigious [[Dick Butkus Award]], given to the most outstanding linebacker in college football. He also won the [[Conerly Trophy#Conerly Trophy|Conerly Trophy]], voted upon by the media in Mississippi and awarded to the best college football player in Mississippi. In addition, he was a finalist for the Bronko Nagurski Award and semi-finalist for both the Rotary Lombardi Award and the Lott Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olemisssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=12787&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600&ATCLID=542726&Q_SEASON=2006&KEY=&DB_OEM_ID=2600&DB_LANG=&IN_SUBSCRIBER_CONTENT= |title=Patrick Willis # 49 |website=University of Mississippi Athletics |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070707123104/http://www.olemisssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=12787&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600&ATCLID=542726&Q_SEASON=2006&KEY=&DB_OEM_ID=2600&DB_LANG=&IN_SUBSCRIBER_CONTENT= |url-status=dead |archivedate=July 7, 2007|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-SEC (2005, 2006)\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-America]]n ([[2005 College Football All-America Team|2005]], [[2006 College Football All-America Team|2006]])\n* SEC Defensive Player of the Year (2006)\n* [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] (2006)\n* [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] (2006)\n* [[Conerly Trophy#Conerly Trophy|Conerly Trophy]] (2006)\n*College football hall of fame Indutee of 2019\n\n==Professional career==\n\nOriginally regarded as a late-first to early-second round draft pick,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/writers/don_banks/01/25/mock.draft1.part3/index.html | work=CNN | title=SI.com \u2013 Mock Draft No. 1 (cont.) \u2013 Jan 26, 2007 | date=January 26, 2007}}</ref> Willis improved his draft stock with an impressive performance at the NFL Combine; his 4.56 40-yard dash<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2007&workout=FORTY_YARD_DASH&position=LB |title=NFL Events: Combine Top Performers |publisher=NFL.com |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft/combine/_/id/30/year/2007/order/false |title=2007 NFL Combine Results \u2013 Linebackers |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"combine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=17257&draftyear=2007&genpos=ILB |title=Patrick Willis &#124; Mississippi, ILB : 2007 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |publisher=NFL Draft Scout |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref> was one of the fastest among linebackers. He also posted a 39-inch vertical jump and recorded 22 repetitions of the 225-lb. bench press. Willis clocked in at 4.38 seconds for his 40-yard dash during his University of Mississippi pro-day workout.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Corbett |first=Jim |date=September 6, 2008 |title=49ers' Willis on way to top of NFL's linebackers corps |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/niners/2008-09-06-willis_N.htm |postscript=<!--None--> }}</ref> Analysts of ''[[The Sporting News]]'' compared him to [[Jeremiah Trotter]].<ref>{{cite web |work=SportingNews.com |date=April 29, 2007 |title=Pro Football War Room: Patrick Willis |url=http://warroom.sportingnews.com/nfl/draft/2007/players/6895.html |postscript=<!--None--> }}</ref> Willis also earned South Team Defensive MVP honors at the 2007 Senior Bowl.\n\nWillis was selected by the [[San Francisco 49ers]] in the first round with the 11th overall pick in the 2007 NFL Draft, re-uniting him with the staff that coached his South Squad at the 2007 Senior Bowl. He signed a seven-year, $53.51&nbsp;million contract with the 49ers in the 2010 season.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Trotter |authorlink= |author2= |title=NFL Rookies: Patrick Willis, MLB, 49ers |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/football/nfl/10/10/rookie.willis/ |work=Sports Illustrated |publisher= |date=October 10, 2007 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 1\u215b\n|       weight = 242\n|         dash = 4.56 <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. The electronic timed 40-yards at the combine have higher priority. See references above. -->\n|    ten split = 1.61\n| twenty split = 2.68\n|      shuttle = 4.46\n|   cone drill = 7.23\n|     vertical = 39\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 11\n|        bench = 22\n|    wonderlic = 12\n|     arm span = 34\n|    hand span = 9\u00be\n|         note = All values from the 2007 [[NFL Combine]]<ref name=\"combine\" /><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://nflcombineresults.com/playerpage.php?i=7838 |title = Patrick Willis &#124; ILB &#124; Mississippi - NFL Combine Results}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2007 season===\n{{Quote box| width=25%|align=right\n|quote = \"I've coached two of the greatest linebackers\u2014one that has already proven to be one of the greatest and one who will prove to be.\"\n|source = NFL Hall of Famer [[Mike Singletary]], referring to [[Ray Lewis (American football)|Ray Lewis]] and Patrick Willis.<ref name=\"CorbettUSAToday\" />}}\nWillis was coached directly by Hall of Fame middle-linebacker/coach [[Mike Singletary]] (who later became 49ers head coach), and eventually started at inside linebacker, specifically the \"Mike\" position, in the 49ers' [[3-4 defense]]. In his first NFL game, Willis recorded 11 tackles, including 9 solo, and a forced fumble as the 49ers defeated the Arizona Cardinals in dramatic fashion by a score of 20\u201317. For his effort, he won the Diet Pepsi Rookie of the Week Award. One of Willis's strongest performances came against the [[Minnesota Vikings]], as he led the 49ers defense in containing [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year|Offensive Rookie of the Year]], [[Adrian Peterson]], who managed just 3 yards on 14 carries. Willis's most impressive statistical performance came in week 16 at home against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. In this game he recorded 20 total tackles, two sacks, one forced fumble and one pass deflected in a 21\u201319 victory, earning Rookie of the Week honors for the fourth time. In addition to receiving the award in weeks 1 and 16, Willis took home the award in weeks 2 and 12. He was also awarded the GMC Defensive Player of the Week twice.\n\nIn a game against the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on November 25, Willis ran down wide receiver [[Sean Morey (American football)|Sean Morey]] after a 62-yard, catch-and-run for the game-saving tackle in overtime. The 49ers eventually won 37\u201331.<ref name=\"CorbettUSAToday\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Corbett |author2= |title=49ers' Willis on way to top of NFL's linebackers corps |work=USA Today |page= |date=September 6, 2008 |accessdate= |quote= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/niners/2008-09-06-willis_N.htm }}</ref>\n\nWillis finished the 2007 campaign with an NFL-leading 174 total tackles, along with four sacks, two forced fumbles, and five passes deflected. According to the 49ers, however, he is unofficially credited with over 200 tackles during that season. As a result, Willis was one of two 49ers selected to the [[2008 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] along with punter [[Andy Lee (American football)|Andy Lee]]. Other honors earned at the conclusion of his first professional season included being named [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year|AP NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]], first-team [[All-Pro]], and [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Linebacker of the Year]]. He was the only rookie in the NFL to make the AP All-Pro squad and the first defensive rookie from the 49ers to make the Pro Bowl since [[Ronnie Lott]] in 1981. His season was capped by being named one of [[ESPN The Magazine]]'s \"NEXT\" athletes of 2008, alongside [[New York Yankees|Yankee]] [[Joba Chamberlain]] and [[Portland Trail Blazers|Trail Blazer]] [[Brandon Roy]].\n\n===2008 season===\n[[File:Patrick Willis on field pregame at Eagles at 49ers 10-12-08.JPG|thumb|right|Willis in October 2008]]\n\nIn his second NFL season, Willis scored his first career NFL [[touchdown]] against Seattle, returning an interception for 86 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140sea.htm |title=San Francisco 49ers at Seattle Seahawks - September 14th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\nOn December 16, during another dominating season with the 49ers, Willis was named the starting inside linebacker for the NFC Pro Bowl team. In just two seasons, he established himself as one of the top linebackers in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story?id=09000d5d80d60467&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true |title=2009 Pro Bowl rosters |publisher=NFL.com |date=February 10, 2009 |accessdate=October 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201210427/http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story?id=09000d5d80d60467&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true |archivedate=February 1, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Willis finished second in tackles and was voted to his second consecutive Pro Bowl, this time as a starter. He was also voted second-team All-Pro, barely missing the first team as [[Jon Beason]] of [[Carolina Panthers]] collected one more vote than Willis.\n\n===2009 season===\nWillis started the season strong in the opener against the Arizona Cardinals. He recorded 14 tackles and an interception in a 20\u201316 win in Arizona. He also had a huge game in week 4 against St. Louis finishing with 8 tackles, 2.5 sacks and an interception return for a 23-yard touchdown.\n\nThe biggest improvement in his game from the previous year was the increased sideline-to-sideline range. Willis made 54 tackles on plays labeled as \"Wide left\" or \"Wide right\" which accounted for 35.5% of his total tackles. In that area, he led all inside linebackers by a large margin. He was also the league leader in impact plays with a total of 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballsfuture.com/nfl/2009/allpro.html |title=2009 All-Pro Team |publisher=Footballsfuture.com |date=September 28, 2006 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Willis accumulated an NFL-leading 152 tackles along with four sacks, three forced fumbles, eight pass deflections and three interceptions. He has now led the league in tackles in two of his first three seasons. Willis also earned first-team [[All-Pro]] receiving 49/50 votes from the AP and was voted to his third consecutive [[Pro Bowl]]. However, shortly before the Pro Bowl, which was set in South Florida, Willis decided to play it safe and opted not to play due to a leg injury he sustained. He stayed in South Florida for the game and stood on the sideline in support of the NFC team and 49er teammates [[Frank Gore]], [[Vernon Davis]], [[Justin Smith (defensive end)|Justin Smith]] and [[Andy Lee (American football)|Andy Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fucillo |first=David |url=http://www.ninersnation.com/2009/12/29/1224534/49ers-lb-patrick-willis-te-vernon |title=49ers LB Patrick Willis, TE Vernon Davis, P Andy Lee named to Pro Bowl |publisher=Niners Nation |date=December 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWillis was named the 2009 [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Linebacker of the Year]], an award voted on by past NFL linebackers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nflalumni.org/Events/SuperBowlWeekend/PlayeroftheYearAwards2009Winners.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118084117/http://www.nflalumni.org/Events/SuperBowlWeekend/PlayeroftheYearAwards2009Winners.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 18, 2010 |title=Player of the Year Awards 2009 Winners |publisher=NFL Alumni Association |accessdate=December 31, 2010 }}</ref> Willis also became the second NFL player to win the [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] since it was expanded in 2008 to include high school and professional winners in part to help end anabolic steroid abuse among young athletes.\n\n===2010 season===\nOn May 4, Willis signed a five-year contract extension worth $50&nbsp;million, with $29&nbsp;million in guaranteed money making him the highest paid inside linebacker in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d817f3d55&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true |title=Hard work pays: Niners LB Willis signs five-year, $50M extension |publisher=NFL.com |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Willis strengthened a dimension of his game, totaling a career-high 6.0 sacks. He played through the season with several injuries, playing a game against the San Diego Chargers with a cast on his broken hand. Willis was ruled out for Week 17 after undergoing a second surgery on his broken right hand. It was the first time that Willis had ever missed a game in his career. Willis had also made a habit of making it to the Pro Bowl. He had gone all four seasons of his NFL career and even with his tackle numbers down (largely due to offenses scheming against him), Willis still finished with the second-most fan votes for inside linebackers in the entire NFL.<ref>{{cite web |last=Price |first=Taylor |url=http://www.49ers.com/news-and-events/article-2/Willis-Smith-Return-to-the-Pro-Bowl/de9bd872-0228-430a-97cd-458d4dae8534 |title=Willis, Smith Return to the Pro Bowl |publisher=49ers.com |date=December 28, 2010 |accessdate=December 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531070334/http://www.49ers.com/news-and-events/article-2/Willis-Smith-Return-to-the-Pro-Bowl/de9bd872-0228-430a-97cd-458d4dae8534 |archive-date=May 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He now joins Hall of Fame safety Ronnie Lott as only 49ers to be selected to the Pro Bowl in each of their first four seasons.\n\nWillis also earned first-team [[All-Pro]] from the Associated Press alongside [[Jerod Mayo]] of the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81de390c/article/brady-afc-players-dominate-selections-on-ap-allpro-team|title=Brady, AFC players dominate selections on AP All-Pro Team |agency=Associated Press |date=January 24, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref> For the third time in his career, and the second year in a row, he was named Linebacker of the Year by the [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/02/07/11/49ers-Willis-named-NFL-Alumni-Linebacker/landing_niners.html?blockID=405971&feedID=2800 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120724091844/http://www.csnbayarea.com/02/07/11/49ers-Willis-named-NFL-Alumni-Linebacker/landing_niners.html?blockID=405971&feedID=2800 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 24, 2012 |title=49ers' Willis named NFL Alumni Linebacker of Year |publisher=CSN Bay Area |date=February 7, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===2011 season===\nBefore the start of the 2011 season, Willis ran away from the field in the voting for the NFL's best linebacker on [[ESPN]].com. \"Nobody in the NFL plays their position better than Patrick Willis, and that is saying a lot,\" said Matt Williamson of Scouts Inc. \"He is as good a linebacker as [[Peyton Manning]] is a quarterback, as [[Andre Johnson]] is a receiver, as [[Adrian Peterson]] is a running back. He has no weaknesses.\"<ref name=\"espn.go.com\">{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/35956/power-rankings-top-10-nfl-linebackers |title=Power Rankings: Top 10 NFL linebackers| publisher=espn.go.com |date=April 12, 2011}}</ref> Even 12-time Pro Bowler [[Ray Lewis]], the dominant linebacker of his era, pointed to Willis as a worthy successor to his undisputed reign. ESPN's [[Dana Jacobson]] asked Lewis which young linebacker reminded him of himself. \"I just love the way he plays the game,\" Lewis said. \"He plays the game with a fire. He reminds me of myself\u2014a lot, a lot, a lot.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/35921/video-ray-lewis-on-patrick-willis|title=Video: Ray Lewis on Patrick Willis| publisher=espn.go.com |date=April 11, 2011}}</ref> Willis also came in fourth in an ESPN expert vote for the NFL's 10 best defensive players, finishing only behind 2010 [[National Football League Defensive Player of the Year Award|AP NFL Defensive Player of the Year]] [[Troy Polamalu]], [[DeMarcus Ware]], and [[Darrelle Revis]].  Also, when he was voted no. 10 players of 2012 (2011 season), [[Ray Rice]] and commentators noted the resemblance in playing style and techniques from Willis to Lewis from 10 years ago<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/top100/2012?module=HP11_hot_topics#video=09000d5d82a2b8ff Top 100 Players of 2012 \u2013 No. 10] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105045213/http://www.nfl.com/top100/2012?module=HP11_hot_topics#video=09000d5d82a2b8ff |date=November 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Willis led a top ranked 49ers defense which set an NFL single season record of not allowing a rushing touchdown until week 16. The previous record was held by the 1920 Decatur Staleys, who did not allow a rushing touchdown in a 13-game season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2011-12-20/sports/30536980_1_kicker-akers-jim-tomsula-braylon-edwards |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=Eric |last=Branch |title=David Akers breaks Rice's 49ers scoring mark |date=December 20, 2011 }}</ref> The 49ers' stingy defense ranked fourth overall and played a huge role in the 49ers finishing with a 13\u20133 record. This also marked the first time since 2002 the 49ers were division champs and back in the [[playoffs]].\n\nDuring a game against the [[St. Louis Rams]] in week 13, Willis landed awkwardly after missing a tackle and injured his right hamstring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=AjX9wDP9AjYuu6B4JgCVVpf.uLYF?gid=20111204025 |title=49ers beat Rams 26\u20130 for 1st playoffs since '02|publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> Despite missing nearly four games due to the hamstring injury, Willis finished the season with 97 tackles along with two sacks, four forced fumbles, 12 pass deflections and an interception. He also improved his game significantly in coverage recording a career-high 12 pass deflections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/27187/power-rankings-top-10-defensive-players |title=Power Rankings: Top 10 defensive players |author1=Seifert, Kevin  |date=May 24, 2011 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Willis was named to his fifth consecutive [[Pro Bowl]] and becomes the first player in franchise history to make five Pro Bowl appearances to start a career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story/09000d5d82578253/article/2012-pro-bowl-rosters |title=2012 Pro Bowl rosters |publisher=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> In addition, he earned first-team [[All-Pro]] from the [[Associated Press]] for the third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2011/1/24/1953991/ap-all-pro-team-patrick-willis-named-to-third-team-in-four-years|title=AP All Pro Team: Patrick Willis Named To Third Team In Four Years|website=SBNation  |date=24 January 2011 |author1=Fucillo, David |accessdate=22 April 2014| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nDuring the 2012 season, Willis had 120 combined tackles, two forced fumbles (one recovery), two interceptions, nine passes defended, and 0.5 sacks. He led the 49ers into the postseason for a second straight year. Willis recorded ten combined tackles as the 49ers lost [[Super Bowl XLVII]] to the [[Baltimore Ravens]] by a score of 34\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201302030sfo.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVII - San Francisco 49ers vs. Baltimore Ravens - February 3rd, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref> Willis had 29 combined tackles and a sack during the 2012 postseason.\n\n===2013 season===\nOn August 5, 2013, Willis underwent surgery to repair a fractured hand he suffered during training camp. He started the first three games of the season, but then had a groin injury in Week 3. He would then miss the next two games. However, in a game against the [[Atlanta Falcons]], he recorded 18 tackles. He ended the 2013 season with 104 tackles.\n\n===2014 season===\nWillis played in six games of the 2014 season hampered by a nagging toe injury. He made the decision to end his season on November 11 and undergo season-ending surgery on his nagging left big toe, which bothered him for several previous seasons. The 49ers placed Willis on the injured reserve list soon after the surgery.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanzus|first1=Dan|title=Patrick Willis (toe) placed on 49ers' season-ending IR|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000426691/article/patrick-willis-toe-placed-on-49ers-seasonending-ir|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter struggling with a toe injury that kept Willis sidelined for most of 2014, he announced his retirement on March 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick Willis Explains Decision to Retire from NFL|url=http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/Patrick-Willis-Explains-Decision-to-Retire-from-NFL/c0afb6ec-0923-4e91-9bef-be7a984990e4|publisher=49ers.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|first=Tyler|last= Emerick}}</ref><ref name=\"willisbutkus09\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olemisssports.com/ |title=OleMissSports.com: Willis Wins Butkus Award As Collegian And Pro |accessdate=November 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWillis was separated from his biological father at the age of 17, with his mother leaving him when he was a child, and along with his three siblings moved in with his parental guardians, Willis' high school basketball coach, Chris Finley, and his wife, Julie.<ref name=\"Two_Dads\">{{citenews|title=A 49ers Linebacker With Two Men to Call Dad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/21/sports/football/49ers-willis-calls-two-men-dad-and-they-are-strikingly-different.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2012|author1=Branch, John}}</ref> Willis's brother, Detris, drowned in 2006 while swimming with his friends.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://florida.scout.com/2/550234.html |title=SEC: Willis suffers more than an injury |date=July 27, 2006 |first=Mark |last=McLeod |work=GatorCountry.com |access-date=October 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022422/http://florida.scout.com/2/550234.html |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Foster\">{{citenews|title=Patrick Willis still holds foster parents dear|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/niners/2013/01/25/patrick-willis-foster-parents-hometown-bruceton-tennessee/1863665/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=January 25, 2013|author1=Brady, Erik }}</ref> His uncle, Arthur Willis, was a professional [[super middleweight]] [[Boxing|boxer]] who later fought future world champion [[James Toney]] to a split decision.<ref>{{boxrec |id=007222 |name=Arthur Willis}}</ref><ref name=\"MMA\">{{cite news |author1=Brown,  Daniel |title=Ex-49ers star Patrick Willis says of NFL return: \u2018Nope, I\u2019m cool\u2019 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/02/15/ex-49ers-star-patrick-willis-showing-fight-in-retirement-says-of-nfl-return-nope-im-cool/ |work=The Mercury News |publisher=Bay Area News Group |date=15 February 2017 |quote=Willis grew up as a fight fan because his uncle was a professional super middleweight boxer. Arthur Willis later fought future world champion James Toney to a split decision.}}</ref>\n\nHe holds a degree in [[criminal justice]] and envisions a future in law enforcement.<ref name=\"49ers media guide\">2010 San Francisco 49ers media guide</ref>\nWillis is a Christian. Willis says his grandmother told him about Jesus. Willis talks about his faith when he plays saying, \"No matter the outcome of a game, my No.1 goal is to glorify God. I always pray, 'Lord, I don't know what today's game is going to be like, but I pray that you bless me to go out here and play for you. Be a soldier for your army, go out here and lead this team the way you want me to lead it.'\"<ref name=\"CBN_God\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbn.com/700club/sports/Patrick-willis-011212.aspx|title=Patrick Willis Gives God the Praise, Glory and Honor|website=The Christian Broadcasting Network|date=12 January 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BCNN1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackchristiannews.com/news/2012/01/patrick-willis-my-1-goal-is-to-glorify-god.html|title=Patrick Willis: My #1 Goal is to Glorify God|publisher=Black Christian News Network One|date=15 January 2012|accessdate=January 2, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102191946/http://www.blackchristiannews.com/news/2012/01/patrick-willis-my-1-goal-is-to-glorify-god.html|archivedate=2 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.willis52.com Official Website]\n*{{Footballstats |nfl=WIL618736 |espn=10455 |cbs= |yahoo=8265 |si=8265 |pfr=WillPa98 |rotoworld=4171}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[http://www.olemisssports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/patrick_willis_142029.html Ole Miss Rebels bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100204001310/http://www.49ers.com/team/roster/patrick-willis/ef5ca421-1c18-4012-ad6f-9b96a1e5e125/ San Francisco 49ers bio]\n*{{cite web |title=Patrick Willis Career Highlights |publisher=NFL.com |via=[[YouTube]] |date=March 9, 2015 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jjHAjAF7BHI&list=PLRdw3IjKY2gmBTpTbGp9NjkIzC6IXWx-b&index=39 }}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Patrick Willis\n|list1=\n{{Dick Butkus Award (collegiate)}}\n{{Conerly Trophy}}\n{{2006 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{2007 NFL Draft}}\n{{49ersFirstPick}}\n{{49ers2007DraftPicks}}\n{{AP Defensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Dick Butkus Award (professional)}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Willis, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:American football middle linebackers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League Defensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Ole Miss Rebels football players]]\n[[Category:People from Carroll County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{For|the judge|Patrick Willis (judge)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Patrick Willis\n|image=Patrick Willis in 2012.jpg\n|image_size=180\n|alt=\n|caption=Willis with the San Francisco 49ers in 2012\n|number=52\n|position=[[Linebacker#Middle linebacker|Middle linebacker]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1985|1|25|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Bruceton, Tennessee]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=1\n|weight_lbs=240\n|high_school=[[Hollow Rock-Bruceton Central High School|Bruceton (TN) Central]]\n|college=[[Ole Miss Rebels football|Mississippi]]\n|draftyear=2007\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=11\n|pastteams=\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{NFL Year|2007}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n|highlights=\n* 7\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2008 Pro Bowl|2007]]\u2013[[2014 Pro Bowl|2013]])\n* 5\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2007 All-Pro Team|2007]], [[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]]\u2013[[2013 All-Pro Team|2012]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2008 All-Pro Team|2008]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2007|2007]])\n* [[Butkus Award|Butkus Award (pro)]] (2009)\n* [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]] (2007)\n* [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award (college)]] (2006)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2005 College Football All-America Team|2005]], [[2006 College Football All-America Team|2006]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2005 All-SEC football team|2005]], [[2006 All-SEC football team|2006]])\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]]\n|statvalue1=950\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack]]s\n|statvalue2=20.5\n|statlabel3=[[Interception]]s\n|statvalue3=8\n|statlabel4=Forced [[fumble]]s\n|statvalue4=16\n|statlabel5=[[Touchdown]]s\n|statvalue5=2\n|nflnew=patrickwillis/2495781\n|CollegeHOF=2444\n}}\n\n'''Patrick L. Willis''' (born January 25, 1985) is a former [[American football]] [[linebacker]] who played his entire eight-year career with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He was drafted by the 49ers in the first round of the [[2007 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Ole Miss Rebels football|University of Mississippi]] and received consensus [[All-American]] honors.\n\nDuring Willis's senior season at Ole Miss, he received the [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] and the [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] as the nation's top linebacker. A year later as a member of the 49ers, Willis led the NFL in tackles, earned first-team [[All-Pro]] and [[Pro Bowl]] honors while being named the 2007 [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year|AP NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]].  Willis made the Pro Bowl in his first seven seasons in the NFL, and earned All-Pro honors in his first six years. He won the college Butkus Award in 2006 while at [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] and in 2009, he won the professional Butkus Award while with the 49ers.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Bruceton, Tennessee]], Willis grew up in abject poverty and had to take care of his younger siblings. By the age of 10, he worked full-time in cotton fields.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/07/patrick-willis_n_5405702.html |title=A Troubled Childhood Shaped Patrick Willis Into A Forgiving Adult And An NFL Powerhouse |last=Schultz |first=Jordan |date=July 7, 2014 |work=Huffington Post |access-date=July 17, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> At age 17, he left his home, a [[double-wide]] in a [[trailer park]] just outside Bruceton, with his brothers, Orey and Detris, and sister, Ernicka, when his alcoholic father turned increasingly violent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/49ers/2012/09/19/patrick-willis-in-powerful-commercial|title=49ers Web Blog: Patrick Willis in powerful commercial/ | work=The San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> The siblings moved in with Willis's high school basketball coach.\n\nWillis attended [[Hollow Rock-Bruceton Central High School]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrbk12.org/Docs/alumni/2000s/2003/patrick_willis/2003_patrick_willis.htm |title=Patrick Willis |publisher=Hrbk12.org |accessdate=October 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726155354/http://www.hrbk12.org/Docs/alumni/2000s/2003/patrick_willis/2003_patrick_willis.htm |archive-date=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> where he was a two-time All-State selection, Regional Most Valuable Player, and West Tennessee Player of the Year. He earned four letters in football and basketball, and three in baseball. He was also the first person in Tennessee state history to be nominated for both the Mr. Football Award for a Lineman (as a linebacker) and the Mr. Football Award for a Back (as a tailback) in the same season.\n\nRegarded as a three-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Willis was listed as the No. 60 linebacker prospect in the class of 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-183 |title=Inside linebackers 2003 |work=Rivals.com |date=February 5, 2010 }}</ref> He chose Ole Miss over Memphis.\n\n{{college athlete recruit start|40=yes|year=2003}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit      = Patrick Willis\n| position     = [[Linebacker|LB]]\n| hometown     = Bruceton, Tennessee\n| highschool   = Central HS\n| feet         = 6\n| inches       = 2\n| weight       =217\n| 40           = 4.6\n| commitdate   = July 8, 2003\n| scout stars  = 2\n| rivals stars = 3\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               = yes\n| year             = 2003\n| rivals ref title = 2003 Mississippi Football Commitment List\n| scout ref title  = 2003 Ole Miss College Football Team Recruiting Prospects\n| rivals school    = olemiss\n| scout s          = 177\n| scout overall    = 32 (college recruiting)\n| rivals overall   = 60 (LB); 38 (college recruiting)\n| accessdate       = August 17, 2013\n| rivals archiveurl=\n| scout archiveurl =\n| espn archiveurl  =\n}}\n\n==College career==\n{{Cquote|Patrick leads by example. He is not a big talker. He just gets in there and does his job every day and makes everybody around him better.|15px|15px|former Mississippi coach [[Ed Orgeron]].<ref name=\"ColstonUSAToday\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Colston |author2= |title=Hardship toughened Willis for NFL's rigors |work=[[USA Today]] |page= |date=March 17, 2007 |accessdate= |quote= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/draft/2007-03-14-patrick-willis_N.htm }}</ref>}}\n\nWillis attended the [[University of Mississippi]] (\"Ole Miss\"), and played for the [[Ole Miss Rebels football]] team from 2003 to 2006.  As a freshman at Ole Miss, Willis played in all 13 games and made 20 stops. He received the Scholar-Athlete Award from the Ole Miss chapter of the [[National Football Foundation]] and [[College Football Hall of Fame]].\n\nAs a sophomore in 2004, he appeared in 10 of 11 games and earned honorable mention All-[[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) honors from the Associated Press. He recorded 70 tackles (54 solo), and led the team with 11.0 tackles for a loss and five sacks.\n\nIn Willis's 2005 junior campaign, he led the SEC in total tackles at 12.80 per game, which placed him sixth nationally. He finished season with 128 total tackles, 9.5 tackles for loss, three sacks, an interception, two forced fumbles and a fumble recovery. Willis was named SEC Defensive Player of the Year by CollegeFootballNews.com and [[Scout.com]]. He was also named as a first-team All-American by College Football News and the All-American Football Foundation. Willis earned first-team All-SEC honors from the Associated Press, SEC Coaches, CollegeFootballNews.com and Rivals.com.<ref name=\"First_Team\">{{cite web|author1= |url=https://olemisssports.com/news/2006/2/27/Patrick_Willis_Named_First_Team_All_America_By_All_American_Football_Foundation.aspx |title=Patrick Willis Named First Team All-America By All-American Football Foundation |website=Ole Miss Football |date=27 February 2006 |accessdate=October 31, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring Willis's last collegiate year in 2006, he led the SEC in tackles once again with 11.4 per game and collected 137 tackles, 11.5 TFLs, seven passes deflected, three sacks, two forced fumbles and one fumble recovery. He was awarded SEC Defensive Player of the Year, first-team All-SEC, and consensus first-team [[2006 College Football All-America Team|All-American]]. He was the winner of the [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] and the prestigious [[Dick Butkus Award]], given to the most outstanding linebacker in college football. He also won the [[Conerly Trophy#Conerly Trophy|Conerly Trophy]], voted upon by the media in Mississippi and awarded to the best college football player in Mississippi. In addition, he was a finalist for the Bronko Nagurski Award and semi-finalist for both the Rotary Lombardi Award and the Lott Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olemisssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=12787&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600&ATCLID=542726&Q_SEASON=2006&KEY=&DB_OEM_ID=2600&DB_LANG=&IN_SUBSCRIBER_CONTENT= |title=Patrick Willis # 49 |website=University of Mississippi Athletics |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070707123104/http://www.olemisssports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=12787&SPID=737&DB_OEM_ID=2600&ATCLID=542726&Q_SEASON=2006&KEY=&DB_OEM_ID=2600&DB_LANG=&IN_SUBSCRIBER_CONTENT= |url-status=dead |archivedate=July 7, 2007|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-SEC (2005, 2006)\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-America]]n ([[2005 College Football All-America Team|2005]], [[2006 College Football All-America Team|2006]])\n* SEC Defensive Player of the Year (2006)\n* [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] (2006)\n* [[Lambert Award|Jack Lambert Award]] (2006)\n* [[Conerly Trophy#Conerly Trophy|Conerly Trophy]] (2006)\n*College football hall of fame Indutee of 2019\n\n==Professional career==\n\nOriginally regarded as a late-first to early-second round draft pick,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/writers/don_banks/01/25/mock.draft1.part3/index.html | work=CNN | title=SI.com \u2013 Mock Draft No. 1 (cont.) \u2013 Jan 26, 2007 | date=January 26, 2007}}</ref> Willis improved his draft stock with an impressive performance at the NFL Combine; his 4.56 40-yard dash<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/top-performers#year=2007&workout=FORTY_YARD_DASH&position=LB |title=NFL Events: Combine Top Performers |publisher=NFL.com |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft/combine/_/id/30/year/2007/order/false |title=2007 NFL Combine Results \u2013 Linebackers |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"combine\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=17257&draftyear=2007&genpos=ILB |title=Patrick Willis &#124; Mississippi, ILB : 2007 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |publisher=NFL Draft Scout |accessdate=March 17, 2011}}</ref> was one of the fastest among linebackers. He also posted a 39-inch vertical jump and recorded 22 repetitions of the 225-lb. bench press. Willis clocked in at 4.38 seconds for his 40-yard dash during his University of Mississippi pro-day workout.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Corbett |first=Jim |date=September 6, 2008 |title=49ers' Willis on way to top of NFL's linebackers corps |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/niners/2008-09-06-willis_N.htm |postscript=<!--None--> }}</ref> Analysts of ''[[The Sporting News]]'' compared him to [[Jeremiah Trotter]].<ref>{{cite web |work=SportingNews.com |date=April 29, 2007 |title=Pro Football War Room: Patrick Willis |url=http://warroom.sportingnews.com/nfl/draft/2007/players/6895.html |postscript=<!--None--> }}</ref> Willis also earned South Team Defensive MVP honors at the 2007 Senior Bowl.\n\nWillis was selected by the [[San Francisco 49ers]] in the first round with the 11th overall pick in the 2007 NFL Draft, re-uniting him with the staff that coached his South Squad at the 2007 Senior Bowl. He signed a seven-year, $53.51&nbsp;million contract with the 49ers in the 2010 season.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Trotter |authorlink= |author2= |title=NFL Rookies: Patrick Willis, MLB, 49ers |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/football/nfl/10/10/rookie.willis/ |work=Sports Illustrated |publisher= |date=October 10, 2007 |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 1\u215b\n|       weight = 242\n|         dash = 4.56 <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. The electronic timed 40-yards at the combine have higher priority. See references above. -->\n|    ten split = 1.61\n| twenty split = 2.68\n|      shuttle = 4.46\n|   cone drill = 7.23\n|     vertical = 39\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 11\n|        bench = 22\n|    wonderlic = 12\n|     arm span = 34\n|    hand span = 9\u00be\n|         note = All values from the 2007 [[NFL Combine]]<ref name=\"combine\" /><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://nflcombineresults.com/playerpage.php?i=7838 |title = Patrick Willis &#124; ILB &#124; Mississippi - NFL Combine Results}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2007 season===\n{{Quote box| width=25%|align=right\n|quote = \"I've coached two of the greatest linebackers\u2014one that has already proven to be one of the greatest and one who will prove to be.\"\n|source = NFL Hall of Famer [[Mike Singletary]], referring to [[Ray Lewis (American football)|Ray Lewis]] and Patrick Willis.<ref name=\"CorbettUSAToday\" />}}\nWillis was coached directly by Hall of Fame middle-linebacker/coach [[Mike Singletary]] (who later became 49ers head coach), and eventually started at inside linebacker, specifically the \"Mike\" position, in the 49ers' [[3-4 defense]]. In his first NFL game, Willis recorded 11 tackles, including 9 solo, and a forced fumble as the 49ers defeated the Arizona Cardinals in dramatic fashion by a score of 20\u201317. For his effort, he won the Diet Pepsi Rookie of the Week Award. One of Willis's strongest performances came against the [[Minnesota Vikings]], as he led the 49ers defense in containing [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year|Offensive Rookie of the Year]], [[Adrian Peterson]], who managed just 3 yards on 14 carries. Willis's most impressive statistical performance came in week 16 at home against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. In this game he recorded 20 total tackles, two sacks, one forced fumble and one pass deflected in a 21\u201319 victory, earning Rookie of the Week honors for the fourth time. In addition to receiving the award in weeks 1 and 16, Willis took home the award in weeks 2 and 12. He was also awarded the GMC Defensive Player of the Week twice.\n\nIn a game against the [[Arizona Cardinals]] on November 25, Willis ran down wide receiver [[Sean Morey (American football)|Sean Morey]] after a 62-yard, catch-and-run for the game-saving tackle in overtime. The 49ers eventually won 37\u201331.<ref name=\"CorbettUSAToday\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Corbett |author2= |title=49ers' Willis on way to top of NFL's linebackers corps |work=USA Today |page= |date=September 6, 2008 |accessdate= |quote= |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/niners/2008-09-06-willis_N.htm }}</ref>\n\nWillis finished the 2007 campaign with an NFL-leading 174 total tackles, along with four sacks, two forced fumbles, and five passes deflected. According to the 49ers, however, he is unofficially credited with over 200 tackles during that season. As a result, Willis was one of two 49ers selected to the [[2008 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] along with punter [[Andy Lee (American football)|Andy Lee]]. Other honors earned at the conclusion of his first professional season included being named [[NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year|AP NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]], first-team [[All-Pro]], and [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Linebacker of the Year]]. He was the only rookie in the NFL to make the AP All-Pro squad and the first defensive rookie from the 49ers to make the Pro Bowl since [[Ronnie Lott]] in 1981. His season was capped by being named one of [[ESPN The Magazine]]'s \"NEXT\" athletes of 2008, alongside [[New York Yankees|Yankee]] [[Joba Chamberlain]] and [[Portland Trail Blazers|Trail Blazer]] [[Brandon Roy]].\n\n===2008 season===\n[[File:Patrick Willis on field pregame at Eagles at 49ers 10-12-08.JPG|thumb|right|Willis in October 2008]]\n\nIn his second NFL season, Willis scored his first career NFL [[touchdown]] against Seattle, returning an interception for 86 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200809140sea.htm |title=San Francisco 49ers at Seattle Seahawks - September 14th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\nOn December 16, during another dominating season with the 49ers, Willis was named the starting inside linebacker for the NFC Pro Bowl team. In just two seasons, he established himself as one of the top linebackers in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story?id=09000d5d80d60467&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true |title=2009 Pro Bowl rosters |publisher=NFL.com |date=February 10, 2009 |accessdate=October 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201210427/http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story?id=09000d5d80d60467&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true |archivedate=February 1, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Willis finished second in tackles and was voted to his second consecutive Pro Bowl, this time as a starter. He was also voted second-team All-Pro, barely missing the first team as [[Jon Beason]] of [[Carolina Panthers]] collected one more vote than Willis.\n\n===2009 season===\nWillis started the season strong in the opener against the Arizona Cardinals. He recorded 14 tackles and an interception in a 20\u201316 win in Arizona. He also had a huge game in week 4 against St. Louis finishing with 8 tackles, 2.5 sacks and an interception return for a 23-yard touchdown.\n\nThe biggest improvement in his game from the previous year was the increased sideline-to-sideline range. Willis made 54 tackles on plays labeled as \"Wide left\" or \"Wide right\" which accounted for 35.5% of his total tackles. In that area, he led all inside linebackers by a large margin. He was also the league leader in impact plays with a total of 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballsfuture.com/nfl/2009/allpro.html |title=2009 All-Pro Team |publisher=Footballsfuture.com |date=September 28, 2006 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the year, Willis accumulated an NFL-leading 152 tackles along with four sacks, three forced fumbles, eight pass deflections and three interceptions. He has now led the league in tackles in two of his first three seasons. Willis also earned first-team [[All-Pro]] receiving 49/50 votes from the AP and was voted to his third consecutive [[Pro Bowl]]. However, shortly before the Pro Bowl, which was set in South Florida, Willis decided to play it safe and opted not to play due to a leg injury he sustained. He stayed in South Florida for the game and stood on the sideline in support of the NFC team and 49er teammates [[Frank Gore]], [[Vernon Davis]], [[Justin Smith (defensive end)|Justin Smith]] and [[Andy Lee (American football)|Andy Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Fucillo |first=David |url=http://www.ninersnation.com/2009/12/29/1224534/49ers-lb-patrick-willis-te-vernon |title=49ers LB Patrick Willis, TE Vernon Davis, P Andy Lee named to Pro Bowl |publisher=Niners Nation |date=December 29, 2009 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWillis was named the 2009 [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Linebacker of the Year]], an award voted on by past NFL linebackers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nflalumni.org/Events/SuperBowlWeekend/PlayeroftheYearAwards2009Winners.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118084117/http://www.nflalumni.org/Events/SuperBowlWeekend/PlayeroftheYearAwards2009Winners.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 18, 2010 |title=Player of the Year Awards 2009 Winners |publisher=NFL Alumni Association |accessdate=December 31, 2010 }}</ref> Willis also became the second NFL player to win the [[Dick Butkus Award|Butkus Award]] since it was expanded in 2008 to include high school and professional winners in part to help end anabolic steroid abuse among young athletes.\n\n===2010 season===\nOn May 4, Willis signed a five-year contract extension worth $50&nbsp;million, with $29&nbsp;million in guaranteed money making him the highest paid inside linebacker in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d817f3d55&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true |title=Hard work pays: Niners LB Willis signs five-year, $50M extension |publisher=NFL.com |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Willis strengthened a dimension of his game, totaling a career-high 6.0 sacks. He played through the season with several injuries, playing a game against the San Diego Chargers with a cast on his broken hand. Willis was ruled out for Week 17 after undergoing a second surgery on his broken right hand. It was the first time that Willis had ever missed a game in his career. Willis had also made a habit of making it to the Pro Bowl. He had gone all four seasons of his NFL career and even with his tackle numbers down (largely due to offenses scheming against him), Willis still finished with the second-most fan votes for inside linebackers in the entire NFL.<ref>{{cite web |last=Price |first=Taylor |url=http://www.49ers.com/news-and-events/article-2/Willis-Smith-Return-to-the-Pro-Bowl/de9bd872-0228-430a-97cd-458d4dae8534 |title=Willis, Smith Return to the Pro Bowl |publisher=49ers.com |date=December 28, 2010 |accessdate=December 31, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531070334/http://www.49ers.com/news-and-events/article-2/Willis-Smith-Return-to-the-Pro-Bowl/de9bd872-0228-430a-97cd-458d4dae8534 |archive-date=May 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He now joins Hall of Fame safety Ronnie Lott as only 49ers to be selected to the Pro Bowl in each of their first four seasons.\n\nWillis also earned first-team [[All-Pro]] from the Associated Press alongside [[Jerod Mayo]] of the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81de390c/article/brady-afc-players-dominate-selections-on-ap-allpro-team|title=Brady, AFC players dominate selections on AP All-Pro Team |agency=Associated Press |date=January 24, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011}}</ref> For the third time in his career, and the second year in a row, he was named Linebacker of the Year by the [[National Football League Alumni|NFL Alumni Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/02/07/11/49ers-Willis-named-NFL-Alumni-Linebacker/landing_niners.html?blockID=405971&feedID=2800 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120724091844/http://www.csnbayarea.com/02/07/11/49ers-Willis-named-NFL-Alumni-Linebacker/landing_niners.html?blockID=405971&feedID=2800 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 24, 2012 |title=49ers' Willis named NFL Alumni Linebacker of Year |publisher=CSN Bay Area |date=February 7, 2011 |accessdate=February 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===2011 season===\nBefore the start of the 2011 season, Willis ran away from the field in the voting for the NFL's best linebacker on [[ESPN]].com. \"Nobody in the NFL plays their position better than Patrick Willis, and that is saying a lot,\" said Matt Williamson of Scouts Inc. \"He is as good a linebacker as [[Peyton Manning]] is a quarterback, as [[Andre Johnson]] is a receiver, as [[Adrian Peterson]] is a running back. He has no weaknesses.\"<ref name=\"espn.go.com\">{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/35956/power-rankings-top-10-nfl-linebackers |title=Power Rankings: Top 10 NFL linebackers| publisher=espn.go.com |date=April 12, 2011}}</ref> Even 12-time Pro Bowler [[Ray Lewis]], the dominant linebacker of his era, pointed to Willis as a worthy successor to his undisputed reign. ESPN's [[Dana Jacobson]] asked Lewis which young linebacker reminded him of himself. \"I just love the way he plays the game,\" Lewis said. \"He plays the game with a fire. He reminds me of myself\u2014a lot, a lot, a lot.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/35921/video-ray-lewis-on-patrick-willis|title=Video: Ray Lewis on Patrick Willis| publisher=espn.go.com |date=April 11, 2011}}</ref> Willis also came in fourth in an ESPN expert vote for the NFL's 10 best defensive players, finishing only behind 2010 [[National Football League Defensive Player of the Year Award|AP NFL Defensive Player of the Year]] [[Troy Polamalu]], [[DeMarcus Ware]], and [[Darrelle Revis]].  Also, when he was voted no. 10 players of 2012 (2011 season), [[Ray Rice]] and commentators noted the resemblance in playing style and techniques from Willis to Lewis from 10 years ago<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/top100/2012?module=HP11_hot_topics#video=09000d5d82a2b8ff Top 100 Players of 2012 \u2013 No. 10] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105045213/http://www.nfl.com/top100/2012?module=HP11_hot_topics#video=09000d5d82a2b8ff |date=November 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Willis led a top ranked 49ers defense which set an NFL single season record of not allowing a rushing touchdown until week 16. The previous record was held by the 1920 Decatur Staleys, who did not allow a rushing touchdown in a 13-game season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2011-12-20/sports/30536980_1_kicker-akers-jim-tomsula-braylon-edwards |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |first=Eric |last=Branch |title=David Akers breaks Rice's 49ers scoring mark |date=December 20, 2011 }}</ref> The 49ers' stingy defense ranked fourth overall and played a huge role in the 49ers finishing with a 13\u20133 record. This also marked the first time since 2002 the 49ers were division champs and back in the [[playoffs]].\n\nDuring a game against the [[St. Louis Rams]] in week 13, Willis landed awkwardly after missing a tackle and injured his right hamstring.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=AjX9wDP9AjYuu6B4JgCVVpf.uLYF?gid=20111204025 |title=49ers beat Rams 26\u20130 for 1st playoffs since '02|publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> Despite missing nearly four games due to the hamstring injury, Willis finished the season with 97 tackles along with two sacks, four forced fumbles, 12 pass deflections and an interception. He also improved his game significantly in coverage recording a career-high 12 pass deflections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/27187/power-rankings-top-10-defensive-players |title=Power Rankings: Top 10 defensive players |author1=Seifert, Kevin  |date=May 24, 2011 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Willis was named to his fifth consecutive [[Pro Bowl]] and becomes the first player in franchise history to make five Pro Bowl appearances to start a career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/probowl/story/09000d5d82578253/article/2012-pro-bowl-rosters |title=2012 Pro Bowl rosters |publisher=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> In addition, he earned first-team [[All-Pro]] from the [[Associated Press]] for the third consecutive year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ninersnation.com/2011/1/24/1953991/ap-all-pro-team-patrick-willis-named-to-third-team-in-four-years|title=AP All Pro Team: Patrick Willis Named To Third Team In Four Years|website=SBNation  |date=24 January 2011 |author1=Fucillo, David |accessdate=22 April 2014| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nDuring the 2012 season, Willis had 120 combined tackles, two forced fumbles (one recovery), two interceptions, nine passes defended, and 0.5 sacks. He led the 49ers into the postseason for a second straight year. Willis recorded ten combined tackles as the 49ers lost [[Super Bowl XLVII]] to the [[Baltimore Ravens]] by a score of 34\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201302030sfo.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVII - San Francisco 49ers vs. Baltimore Ravens - February 3rd, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 2, 2017}}</ref> Willis had 29 combined tackles and a sack during the 2012 postseason.\n\n===2013 season===\nOn August 5, 2013, Willis underwent surgery to repair a fractured hand he suffered during training camp. He started the first three games of the season, but then had a groin injury in Week 3. He would then miss the next two games. However, in a game against the [[Atlanta Falcons]], he recorded 18 tackles. He ended the 2013 season with 104 tackles.\n\n===2014 season===\nWillis played in six games of the 2014 season hampered by a nagging toe injury. He made the decision to end his season on November 11 and undergo season-ending surgery on his nagging left big toe, which bothered him for several previous seasons. The 49ers placed Willis on the injured reserve list soon after the surgery.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanzus|first1=Dan|title=Patrick Willis (toe) placed on 49ers' season-ending IR|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000426691/article/patrick-willis-toe-placed-on-49ers-seasonending-ir|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter struggling with a toe injury that kept Willis sidelined for most of 2014, he announced his retirement on March 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick Willis Explains Decision to Retire from NFL|url=http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/Patrick-Willis-Explains-Decision-to-Retire-from-NFL/c0afb6ec-0923-4e91-9bef-be7a984990e4|publisher=49ers.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015|first=Tyler|last= Emerick}}</ref><ref name=\"willisbutkus09\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olemisssports.com/ |title=OleMissSports.com: Willis Wins Butkus Award As Collegian And Pro |accessdate=November 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWillis was separated from his biological father at the age of 17, with his mother leaving him when he was a child, and along with his three siblings moved in with his parental guardians, Willis' high school basketball coach, Chris Finley, and his wife, Julie.<ref name=\"Two_Dads\">{{citenews|title=A 49ers Linebacker With Two Men to Call Dad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/21/sports/football/49ers-willis-calls-two-men-dad-and-they-are-strikingly-different.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2012|author1=Branch, John}}</ref> Willis's brother, Detris, drowned in 2006 while swimming with his friends.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://florida.scout.com/2/550234.html |title=SEC: Willis suffers more than an injury |date=July 27, 2006 |first=Mark |last=McLeod |work=GatorCountry.com |access-date=October 20, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022422/http://florida.scout.com/2/550234.html |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Foster\">{{citenews|title=Patrick Willis still holds foster parents dear|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/niners/2013/01/25/patrick-willis-foster-parents-hometown-bruceton-tennessee/1863665/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=January 25, 2013|author1=Brady, Erik }}</ref> His uncle, Arthur Willis, was a professional [[super middleweight]] [[Boxing|boxer]] who later fought future world champion [[James Toney]] to a split decision.<ref>{{boxrec |id=007222 |name=Arthur Willis}}</ref><ref name=\"MMA\">{{cite news |author1=Brown,  Daniel |title=Ex-49ers star Patrick Willis says of NFL return: \u2018Nope, I\u2019m cool\u2019 |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/02/15/ex-49ers-star-patrick-willis-showing-fight-in-retirement-says-of-nfl-return-nope-im-cool/ |work=The Mercury News |publisher=Bay Area News Group |date=15 February 2017 |quote=Willis grew up as a fight fan because his uncle was a professional super middleweight boxer. Arthur Willis later fought future world champion James Toney to a split decision.}}</ref>\n\nHe holds a degree in [[criminal justice]] and envisions a future in law enforcement.<ref name=\"49ers media guide\">2010 San Francisco 49ers media guide</ref>\nWillis is a Christian. Willis says his grandmother told him about Jesus. Willis talks about his faith when he plays saying, \"No matter the outcome of a game, my No.1 goal is to glorify God. I always pray, 'Lord, I don't know what today's game is going to be like, but I pray that you bless me to go out here and play for you. Be a soldier for your army, go out here and lead this team the way you want me to lead it.'\"<ref name=\"CBN_God\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbn.com/700club/sports/Patrick-willis-011212.aspx|title=Patrick Willis Gives God the Praise, Glory and Honor|website=The Christian Broadcasting Network|date=12 January 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"BCNN1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackchristiannews.com/news/2012/01/patrick-willis-my-1-goal-is-to-glorify-god.html|title=Patrick Willis: My #1 Goal is to Glorify God|publisher=Black Christian News Network One|date=15 January 2012|accessdate=January 2, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102191946/http://www.blackchristiannews.com/news/2012/01/patrick-willis-my-1-goal-is-to-glorify-god.html|archivedate=2 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.willis52.com Official Website]\n*{{Footballstats |nfl=WIL618736 |espn=10455 |cbs= |yahoo=8265 |si=8265 |pfr=WillPa98 |rotoworld=4171}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[http://www.olemisssports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/patrick_willis_142029.html Ole Miss Rebels bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100204001310/http://www.49ers.com/team/roster/patrick-willis/ef5ca421-1c18-4012-ad6f-9b96a1e5e125/ San Francisco 49ers bio]\n*{{cite web |title=Patrick Willis Career Highlights |publisher=NFL.com |via=[[YouTube]] |date=March 9, 2015 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jjHAjAF7BHI&list=PLRdw3IjKY2gmBTpTbGp9NjkIzC6IXWx-b&index=39 }}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Patrick Willis\n|list1=\n{{Dick Butkus Award (collegiate)}}\n{{Conerly Trophy}}\n{{2006 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{2007 NFL Draft}}\n{{49ersFirstPick}}\n{{49ers2007DraftPicks}}\n{{AP Defensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Dick Butkus Award (professional)}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Willis, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:American football middle linebackers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:National Football League Defensive Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Ole Miss Rebels football players]]\n[[Category:People from Carroll County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sa