{"title_page": "Heraklion International Airport", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Heraklion International Airport<br />\"Nikos Kazantzakis\"\n| nativename   = \u0394\u03b9\u03b5\u03b8\u03bd\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03c2 \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5<br />\"\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b6\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2\"\n| image        = Heraklion International airport.png\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = HER\n| ICAO         = LGIR\n| pushpin_map            = Greece\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Greece\n| pushpin_label          = HER\n| pushpin_label_position = right\n| opened       = {{Start date|1937}}\n| type         = Public / Military\n| owner        = Greek State\n| city-served  = [[Heraklion]]\n| location     = [[Heraklion]], [[Greece]]\n| hub          = <div>\n*[[Bluebird Airways]]\n*[[Sky Express (Greece)|Sky Express]]\n| focus_city   = <div>\n*[[Aegean Airlines]] \n*[[Ellinair]]\n| elevation-f  = 115\n| elevation-m  = 35\n| coordinates  = {{coord|35|20|23|N|25|10|49|E|type:airport_region:GR-91|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = <!-- DO NOT ADD heraklionairport.net or heraklion-airport.info, neither is the airport's official website. -->\n |metric-rwy   = Y\n |r1-number    = 09/27\n |r1-length-f  = 8,800\n |r1-length-m  = 2,714\n |r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n |r2-number    = 12/30\n |r2-length-f  = 5,138\n |r2-length-m  = 1,566\n |r2-surface   = Asphalt\n|stat-year    = 2019\n|stat1-header = Passengers\n|stat1-data   = 7,933,558\n|stat2-header = Passenger traffic change \n|stat2-data   = {{decrease}} 2.0%\n|stat3-header = Aircraft movements \n|stat3-data   = 52,294\n|stat4-header = Aircraft movements change\n|stat4-data   = {{decrease}} 6.1%\n |footnotes    = Sources: Runways<ref>{{cite web |url=http://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=GR91005 |title=Nikos Kazantzakis |accessdate=13 November 2013 |publisher=WorldAeroData}}</ref> Statistics: [[Hellenic Civil Aviation Authority]]<ref name=ypa.gr>{{cite web|url=http://www.ypa.gr/en/profile/statistics/|title=Hellenic Civil Aviation Authority - Statistics|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Heraklion International Airport \"Nikos Kazantzakis\"''' {{airport codes|HER|LGIR}} is the primary airport on the [[island]] of [[Crete]], [[Greece]], and the country's [[List of the busiest airports in Greece|second busiest airport]] after [[Athens International Airport]]. It is located about 5&nbsp;km east of the main city centre of [[Heraklion]], near the municipality of [[Nea Alikarnassos]].  It is a shared civil/military facility.  The airport is named after Heraklion native [[Nikos Kazantzakis]], a Greek writer and philosopher. Nikos Kazantzakis Airport is Crete's main and busiest airport, serving [[Heraklion]] (\u0397\u03c1\u03ac\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf), [[Agios Nikolaos, Crete|Aghios Nikolaos]] (\u0386\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03b1\u03bf\u03c2), [[Malia, Crete|Malia]] (M\u03ac\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1), [[Hersonissos]] (\u03a7\u03b5\u03c1\u03c3\u03cc\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03bf\u03c2), [[Stalida]] (\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03af\u03b4\u03b1), [[Elounda]] (\u0395\u03bb\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1) and other resorts.\n\nA new airport for Heraklion, located 39&nbsp;km to the south-east of the city at [[Kastelli, Heraklion|Kasteli]], is under construction and due to open by 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gtp.gr/2019/02/22/kasteli-airport-deal-signed-project-ready-take-off/|title=Kasteli Airport Deal Signed, Project Ready to Take Off|date=2019-02-22|website=GTP Headlines|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Once completed, the new [[Kasteli Airport|Kasteli International Airport]] will replace the current Heraklion International Airport as the hub for central Crete.\n\n==History==\nThe airport first opened in March 1939.  This was then merely a piece of flat agricultural land.  The first aeroplane (a [[Junkers Ju 52]]) carried the first passengers to the site.  During the [[Second World War]] operations ceased, but in the fall of 1946 traffic resumed, introducing the [[DC-3]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heraklion Airport History|url=http://www.heraklion-airport.info/history.html|work=www.heraklion-airport.info|accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt first, the airport only offered very basic service, with only primitive installations on the site, in the form of three tents, smoke for wind determination and storm lamps for runway lighting.\n\nIn 1947, the first (small) terminal was erected. [[Hellenic Airlines]] started commercial flights in 1948. At that time, a total of 4,000 people were served. The year 1953 saw the construction of a paved runway which was initially 1,850 meters long and oriented as 09/27. The next major event followed in 1954, when a four-engined [[DC-4]] aircraft landed for the first time at the airport. In that year the airport handled approximately 18,000 passengers. From 1957 onward, the new [[Olympic Airways]] used the airport, starting services with the [[Douglas DC-6|DC-6]] aircraft. Jojo AIr also flew here but ended service on July 2, 2001.\n\nFrom 1968 until 1971, the runway was extended to 2,680 meters and a new terminal and other facilities were constructed, essentially making it a new airport. On March 18, 1971, the first charter flight from abroad ([[British Airways]]) operated at the airport. The new airport itself was officially inaugurated on May 5, 1972.\n\n== Terminal Extension ==\n{{prose|date=August 2018}}\nThe latest airport expansion projects began in October 2017. The projects will be entirely financed by the Duty Free Shops SA, in agreement with the Ministry of Infrastructure and Transport and the Hellenic Ministry of Waters, without any cost to the Greek government, include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekriti.gr/kriti-irakleio/prohoroyn-ta-erga-sto-aerodromio-irakleioy-pote-paradidetai-neo-ktirio-foto#sthash.tL6z5A0S.dpbs|title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ad\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 - \u03a0\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03b4\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03bd\u03ad\u03bf \u03ba\u03c4\u03af\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf (\u03c6\u03c9\u03c4\u03bf)|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.athina984.gr/2017/09/25/chr-spirtzis-choris-kostos-gia-to-dimosio-i-epektasi-tou-aerodromiou-irakliou/|title=\u03a7\u03c1. \u03a3\u03c0\u03af\u03c1\u03c4\u03b6\u03b7\u03c2: \"\u03a7\u03c9\u03c1\u03af\u03c2 \u03ba\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf \u03b7 \u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.efsyn.gr/arthro/pairnei-mprosta-i-epektasi-toy-aerodromioy-nikos-kazantzakis|title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03af\u03c1\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03bc\u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac \u03b7 \u03b5\u03c0\u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \"\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b6\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efsyn.gr/arthro/parahorithike-i-ektasi-gia-tin-anavathmisi-toy-aerodromioy-irakleioy|title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b7 \u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b2\u03ac\u03b8\u03bc\u03b9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n<ul>\n<li>the redesign of the layout of the ground and the first floors of the airport</li>\n<li>the expansion of the terminal by 2,900 m<sup>2</sup>), an extension of 17 meters to the airside</li>\n<li>the renovation of a further 8,000 m<sup>2</sup>) within the existing terminal</li>\n<li>the increase in the number of gates for arrivals and departures of passengers</li>\n<li>integration of the arrival hall</li>\n<li>the modification of a luggage belt, so that passengers are not required to queues for their receipt</li>\n<li>improve the operation of electronic ticketing</li>\n<li>upgrading the video ad system</li>\n<li>the modernization of air conditioning in the arrivals hall (budget 700.000 Euros)</li>\n</ul>\n\nThe latest extension began on October 2017 and was completed on 30 March 2018, in time for the airport's high season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cretalive.gr/crete/ayto-einai-to-neo-aerodromio|title=\u0391\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc \u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf ... \u03bd\u03ad\u03bf \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf !|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekriti.gr/kriti-irakleio/eikones-apo-toys-neoys-horoys-toy-aerodromioy-nikos-kazantzakis#sthash.ZBE1SjBf.dpbs|title=\u0395\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bd\u03ad\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c7\u03ce\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \"\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03b6\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b6\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=